                  </hi>. I am ostler to Henry Osborne and others, in Gray's Inn-lane—I saw this bridle safe in the stable on the 8th of February, and missed it next morning.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18390304-name-119" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18390304-name-119" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390304-name-119" type="surname" value="DEAR"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390304-name-119" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN DEAR</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">City police-constable, No.</hi> 158.) About half-past five o'clock on the morning of the 9th of February, I saw the prisoner standing about the coach-rank in Farringdon-street—I went towards him to send him away—he saw me and ran away—I pursued him, and as he turned the corner of Farringdon-market, he threw this bridle into some baskets—I secured him and took it up.</p>
               <p>(<hi rend="italic">Property produced, and sworn to.</hi>)</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner's Defence.</hi> I went to Mr. Osborne's stables, as a <hi rend="italic">lot</hi> of boys go there in a morning to get a ride—a boy there said to me, "Take this bridle and sell it for 4<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.—I will give you 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. out of it, and meet me at the corner of Field-lane."</p>
